SQL data types:

Numeric Types:
INT or INTEGER: Whole numbers (e.g., 1, 100, -5)
DECIMAL(p,s) or NUMERIC(p,s): Exact decimal numbers (e.g., for money)
FLOAT: Floating-point numbers
SMALLINT: Small range integers
BIGINT: Large range integers

String/Character Types:
VARCHAR(n): Variable-length string with max length n
CHAR(n): Fixed-length string
TEXT: Variable unlimited length text

Date and Time Types:
DATE: Date only (YYYY-MM-DD)
TIME: Time only (HH:MM:SS)
TIMESTAMP: Both date and time
DATETIME: Date and time combination

Boolean Type:
BOOLEAN or BOOL: True/False values


Binary Types:
BLOB: Binary Large Object
BINARY: Fixed-length binary data
VARBINARY: Variable-length binary data

Most Frequently Used:
INT: For IDs, counts, ages
VARCHAR: For names, addresses, variable text
DATE/TIMESTAMP: For dates and timestamps
DECIMAL: For precise monetary values
BOOLEAN: For yes/no flags

Best Practices:
Use INT for primary keys/IDs
Use VARCHAR instead of CHAR for variable text
Use DECIMAL for financial calculations
Use TIMESTAMP for audit trails/logging
Use appropriate size limits to optimize storage


